{"type":"message","id":"f076192e","parentId":"41f4acde","timestamp":"2026-04-14T13:18:21.423Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me compare the current sessions against the heartbeat state.\n\n**Last heartbeat state (12:46 UTC):**\n- `cron:ed2d0b5d` — running, lastSeen 12:46 UTC\n- `cron:6f3323ef` — running, lastSeen 12:46 UTC\n- `telegram:group:-5163901258` — running, lastSeen 12:14 UTC\n- `telegram:group:-5168104492` — done, lastSeen 12:46 UTC\n- `telegram:direct:6053576134` — done, lastSeen 12:46 UTC\n\n\n- `main` — done, lastSeen 12:46 UTC\n- `cron:e7885813` — running, lastSeen 12:34 UTC\n- `cron:b653a6c0` — running (STALE zombie), lastSeen 11:53 UTC\n\nI'm noticing the `cron:ac986a8d` entry has a discrepancy—it shows as done in the heartbeat state with an endedAt timestamp, but the note mentions it's absent from the sessions list. Let me reconcile that.\n\nLooking at the current sessions as of 13:17 UTC, I can see several cron jobs are still running: `cron:ed2d0b5d`, `cron:6f3323ef`, and `cron:e7885813`, though the last one appears to have been aborted. There are also completed sessions and one marked as the main agent session that I need to verify.\n\nThe key thing I'm noticing is that `cron:b653a6c0` and `cron:ac986a8d` are no longer showing up in the sessions list, which suggests they've been cleaned up or expired since the last heartbeat state was recorded at 12:46 UTC.\n\nWhat's interesting is that this current cron job `ed2d0b5d` was updated at 13:17:41 UTC, which is more recent than the heartbeat timestamp—that suggests it's actively running and processing right now.\n\nComparing this to the last heartbeat state from 12:46 UTC, all the major cron jobs are still active and running with updated timestamps: `ed2d0b5d` at 13:17, `6f3323ef` at 13:14, and `e7885813` at 13:12, while `b653a6c0` has dropped off the list. Looking at the rest of the session statuses, I can see several are still running or completed without any significant changes since the last heartbeat. The `telegram:direct:6053576134` session finished around 13:09, and the main session ended at 13:06, while the cron job that was aborted appears to have recovered by 13:12.\n\nWhat's notable is that the previously stale `cron:b653a6c0` is now completely absent from the sessions list, which suggests it either finished and was cleaned up or expired from the active list. The most recent activity I'm seeing is from `cron:ed2d0b5d` at 13:17, indicating the monitoring system is still running and detecting heartbeat updates.\n\nLooking at the actual session data more carefully, there's been a clear state transition: the zombie cron `b653a6c0` has disappeared entirely, and the other sessions remain in their previous states with updated timestamps. There's also a new cron job that started at 13:12:33 for agent status reporting, which is a fresh addition to the ecosystem. Looking at the sessions more carefully, I can see that `cron:e7885813` transitioned from a stale state to actively running with a fresh heartbeat at 13:12:33 UTC, while the zombie session `cron:b653a6c0` has completely disappeared from the list. The main session is now marked as done, and there's a new cron entry that started at 13:12:33 but was aborted.\n\nThe key changes since the last heartbeat are the reactivation of `cron:e7885813`, the removal of the zombie session, and the fact that `telegram:group:-5163901258` hasn't shown activity since 12:14 UTC—though it's still listed as running in the heartbeat state, so it might just be idle rather than dead.\n\nLooking at what actually warrants reporting: the zombie `cron:b653a6c0` naturally expired, `cron:e7885813` recovered and resumed, and all the core monitoring systems (`cron:ed2d0b5d`, `cron:6f3323ef`, `cron:e7885813`) are operational. The pipeline looks healthy despite those session state transitions.\n\nI need to compose a report to send to the group. Now I'm looking at the Telegram group sessions and their status updates across the timeline. The group session at -5163901258 was active around 12:14 UTC and hasn't shown new activity since, but there's a discrepancy in the updatedAt timestamp between when the heartbeat last saw it versus when the session list recorded it. I'm realizing the updatedAt timestamp might not reflect message activity for telegram sessions—they're marked running when the session itself is active, regardless of whether new messages came in. The real issue is whether sending a report will cause duplicate notifications since the cron already delivered something, so I should verify the current state and then update the heartbeat file to reflect these changes before deciding on the report.","thinkingSignature":"e32a6e450347dcff3d4501018fadc425ddd92b4b25d19ac0cff5660a477ff027"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_4u1uf4tzfzsw_1","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/root/.openclaw/workspaces2/v4-ecosystem-review/master-orchestrator/memory/heartbeat-state.json","offset":1,"limit":5}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"ahvholding","model":"AHV-Holding-DEV","usage":{"input":969,"output":1193,"cacheRead":14272,"cacheWrite":6774,"totalTokens":23208,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776172678601,"responseId":"062d7187282359a49785775c93decb8d"}}
